\begin{align*}
x-y&=12\quad\text{and}\\
xy&=45.
\end{align*}
Solving for $y$ in the first equation, we get $y = x-12$. Substituting this into the second equation, we get:
\begin{align*}
x(x-12)&=45\\
x^2-12x-45&=0\\
(x-15)(x+3)&=0.
\end{align*}
Since $x$ cannot be negative, we get $x = 15$ and $y = 3$. Thus, the sum of the integers is $15+3 = \boxed{18}$. </think> <answer> 18 </answer>
